'''Merinews''' is an English-language [[online newspaper]] in India built on the concept of [[citizen journalism]].<ref>Citizen Journalism and Human Rights in North East India. "{{cite web |url=http://waccglobal.org/en/20073-media-and-terror/462-Citizen-journalism-and-human-rights-in-north-east-India.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325202030/http://waccglobal.org/en/20073-media-and-terror/462-Citizen-journalism-and-human-rights-in-north-east-India.html |archivedate=25 March 2012 |df=dmy-all }}", WACC Global Report</ref> The website is owned by Bizsol Advisors Pvt. Ltd. and allows anyone to share news, opinion, analysis, reviews, photos and events.<ref name="mid-day.com">Thriving Citizen Journalism in India "[http://www.mid-day.com/lifestyle/2011/sep/140911-Journalism-goes-into-the-slums.htm]", Mid Day, 4 September 2011</ref> Merinews also has city based local print editions in metropolitan areas in India.<ref>Merinews launches city based monthly tabloid" [http://www.indiadigitalreview.com/news/merinewscom-launches-monthly-print-tabloid-gurgaon]", India Digital Review</ref>
Launched in 2006,<ref name="RanganathanRodrigues2010">{{cite book|author1=Maya Ranganathan|author2=Usha M Rodrigues|title=Indian Media in a Globalised World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HvyHAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA112|date=8 July 2010|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-81-321-0599-2|pages=112–}}</ref> Merinews was started by Vipul Kant Upadhyay, who started with no journalism background.<ref>Merinews CEO speaks at AMIC Conference "[http://snurb.info/node/790]", Snurb</ref> In 2011 Merinews was India's largest citizen journalism portal.<ref name="ClarkeBromley2011">{{cite book|author1=Judith Clarke|author2=Michael Bromley|title=International News in the Digital Age: East-West Perceptions of A New World Order|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GBypAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA157|date=18 August 2011|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-64228-9|pages=157–}}</ref>
==Business model== Merinews publications consist of [[user-generated content]], where citizens play the role of journalists and share news, opinion, analysis, event details etc. The content isn't published directly as in a blog or social media platform, but is instead screened by the inhouse editorial team<ref name="mid-day.com"/> Revenue is generated primarily through advertisement served with the content. As of 2013, merinews has also started publishing online local editions,<ref>Merinews launches city specific sections" [http://www.indiadigitalreview.com/news/merinewscom-launches-monthly-print-tabloid-gurgaon]", India Digital Review</ref> complemented by city specific local print tabloids.<ref>Merinews launches city based monthly tabloid" [http://www.indiadigitalreview.com/news/merinews-launches-city-specific-section-local-starts-gurgaon-and-plans-8-more]", India Digital Review</ref>
==Recognition== Merinews received the Manthan Award for Best e-content in 2006 in the e-news category.<ref>Merinews wins Manthan Awards in 2006 "{{cite web |url=http://manthanaward.org/section_full_story.asp?id=514 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017144830/http://manthanaward.org/section_full_story.asp?id=514 |archivedate=17 October 2012 |df=dmy-all }}" Digital Inclusion for Development</ref>
In 2007, merinews was the first Indian website to make the list of ‘Official Honoree’ at the Webby Awards.<ref name="RanganathanRodrigues2010" /><ref>Webby Honorees for 2007 in News Category "{{cite web |url=http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current_honorees.php?media_id=96&category_id=45&season=11 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-02-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091001033015/http://www.webbyawards.com/webbys/current_honorees.php?media_id=96 |archivedate=1 October 2009 |df=dmy-all }}" Webby Awards</ref>
